<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/a0952f4b08b755a7f2b806b4f37e79a6> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "David werd geboren rond 1927 en is overleden in juni 1999. Hij schilderde sinds 1960 in Ramingining waar hij ook woonde. Hij sprak Manyarrngu. David was een belangrijke man in zijn gemeenschap en een inspirerend voorbeeld voor veel Aboriginal kunstenaars. In 1996 kreeg David een eredoctoraat van de Australian National University. David heeft een belangrijke rol gespeeld in de ontwikkeling van het schilderen op boombast in Centraal Arnhem Land. Persoonlijke thema's die hij verwerkte in zijn schilderijen waren de King Brown Snake (Darrpa), de Djang'kawu Sisters en de White Berry Tree. Naast het schilderen beheerste David ook de kunst van het beeldhouwen. Davids werk wordt zeer gewaardeerd over de hele wereld en is in veel museumcollecties te vinden.\r\n\r\nBron: Franca Meeuwsen, Aboriginal Kunst, de verhalen vertellen, Waanders Uitgevers, Zwolle, Aboriginal Art Museum, Utrecht, 2000.\r\n\r\nPROFILE\r\n\r\nDAVID  MALANGI\r\n\r\nThis artist was born in the bush at Mulanga, on the mainland opposite Milingimbi, and went to live at Milingimbi Mission when he was a little boy to be educated. He underwent his age-grading rites at his homeland centre, Yathalamarra before World II. During the war he went back to live at Milingimbi and witnessed bombing from there. After the war he worked for the Mission, erecting fences and gardening. Here he also married his promised wife, Elsie Ganbadha. He continued to work at Milingimbi doing stock work and building mud brick houses for the people.\r\n\r\nDuring all this time, however, he kept taking lengthy breaks to go across to the mainland by canoe to his homeland area, Yathalamarra, and in the late fifties he decided to live there permanently, with all his wives and children.\r\nThe country belongs to his mother and some of his wives. He is now the ceremonial leader of the Manharrngu Clan, which owns vast tracts of land on the eastern and western banks of the Glyde River and the land where Ramingining barge landing has been built, on the shores of the Arafura Sea.\r\n\r\nThere are strings of beautiful freshwater billabongs throughout the area, and David has made his permanent camp beside the Yathalamarra billabong, created in the Dreamtime by the Djankawu Sisters. He and his family grubbed out by hand a dirt road leading from Ramingining to his camp, a distance of 20 kilometres from Ramingining township.\r\n\r\nDavid is most famous for his depiction of the Gurrumarringu Ceremony, part of the Manharrngu Mortuary rites, and this was reproduced without his permission on the one dollar note, which has now been replaced by a coin.\r\nWhen he found out about it he was very angry, as were several white people who fought for recognition and compensation for him, eventually winning a sum of $ 10,000, plus a boat and a medallion from the Reserve Bank. Since then he has always referred to himself as the \"dollar note man\".\r\n\r\nBorn in 1927, David no longer paints the dollar note man on bark, and those small paintings which he does do exhibit very thick line work. Collectors who have any of his earlier works rarely part with them, realising that the value of his paintings will increase with every passing year.\r\n\r\nGURRUMARRINGU THE ANCESTRAL HUNTER\r\n\r\nIn the Dreamtime Gurrumarringu was famous for his skill as a hunter, and the clan group looked to him to supply most of their food, particularly kangaroos and wallabies. He had a beautiful wife called Durandur who loved to sit around the freshwater billabong down the hill from their camp, and talk to all the animals and birds which came to drink from it. She made her husband promise that he would never harm any of these creatures, but would hunt a long way from the camp.\r\n\r\nOnce the Dry Season approached Gurrumarringu found that he had to go further and further afield to find sufficient food. One day he speared a large kangaroo, which he carried on his shoulders, reaching the billabong in the dusk of the evening. He threw the kangaroo on the ground and stretched out for a rest, but instead fell asleep. A large King Brown snake lived beneath the stringybark tree with white berries on it, and he had often watched the hunter and his wife and become very jealous of him. So he slid out from his hole beneath the tree and bit him, killing him instantly.\r\n\r\nNot long afterwards Durandur came down to get water for the camp and found her husband dead. She ran back and told the rest of the clan, and they all gathered around his body to weep and wail at their loss. Then they decided to hold a big ceremony in honour of Gurrumarringu, and this became the first mortuary ceremony of the Manharrngu clan, on which all future ceremonies were based, incorporated with the Morning Star funeral rites. The kangaroo was dissected and cooked, to be eaten by the performers during the ritual.\r\n\r\nIn this painting the artist has depicted Gurrumarringu standing in the centre of the painting, with the snake beside him. On either side of him are two clapstick players, with the didjeridu man above his head. Parts of a dissected kangaroo ready for cooking are shown. Scattered throughout the painting are leaves and caterpillars, which feature in the ceremony.\r\n\r\nTwo stringybark trees with white berries are seen on either side of the painting. One represents the symbolic Morning Star pole bound with bush string, with long streamers ending in tassels of white feathers representing stars, which is placed in the centre of the Manharrngu ceremonial ground.\r\nThe other represents the sacred tree growing on Bralgu, the Island of Spirits, from which Barnumbirr, the Morning Star, sets off on its journey to various groups in Arnhem Land, bringing back the spirits of the dead in its wake.\r\n\r\nDe term Gurrmirringu wordt gebruikt voor het eerste volk van de Manharrngu-clan en voor een bepaalde Voorouder, een machtige krijger, jager en man van de wet. Hij maakte lange reizen naar Ngorunyuwa en Mulanga, de oosterlijke oever van de Glyde River, al jagend en voedsel verzamelend als witte bosbessen en yams. Toen hij naar het noorden keek, zak hij de rook van de kampvuren van het voor de kust gelegen Crocodile Island. Hij gooide een speer die in een rots veranderde net voorbij de monding van de rivier. Er wordt wel verteld dat deze rots Gurrmirringu zelf is. Een ander verhaal zegt dat hij is gestorven door de beet van de King Brown Snake (bruine koningsslang). Gurrmirringu is verbonden met de King Brown Snake, de Death Adder en de witte bosbessen en yams die hij verzamelde.\r\n\r\nDavid Malangi heeft het verhaal van Gurrmirringu een aantal keren geschilderd. Het thema refereert ook aan de rouwceremonies van de Manharrngu-clan.\r\nToen Australië in 1966 overging op het decimale stelsel en er nieuwe bankbiljetten moesten worden gemaakt, verscheen deze schildering van Malangi op de achterkant van het nieuwe één dollar biljet. De ontwerper van de bankbiljetten had een zwartwitfoto van het schilderij en ging er gemakshalve van uit dat het schilderij was gemaakt door een anonieme kunstenaar die al lang was overleden. De zaak haalde de pers en de in verlegenheid gebrachte directeur van de bank gaf opdracht de kunstenaar op te sporen en te belonen. David Malangi kreeg duizend dollar, een viskoffer en een zilveren medaille waar hij erg trots op is." .
